{"title": "Younger Mentor, Older Disciple", "content": "In most cases, the mentor has many years of experience in the topic their student is taking lessons for. The reason for this is often because they are older and have seen more than their young disciple.\n\nThat is not necessarily the case here. For this instance, the mentor is actually a few, or even many, years younger than their disciple. The precise reasons for this may vary, but it always comes down to the fact that the younger person grasps the given subject matter better than the older student on a theoretical and/or practical level, making them a valuable source of knowledge. Think about how in Real Life, younger individuals may often find themselves teaching the older people in their life how to use newer pieces of technology and you get the idea.\n\nSomething to note is that if the mentor looks younger than their pupil, but is actually older than them, it is a case of Square Peg, Round Trope. That being said, this trope can come into play from the opposite spectrum, especially if the student looks younger than the mentor but is Really 700 Years Old.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/YoungerMentorOlderDisciple", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/LyricalNanoha", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MahouSenseiNegima", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/Overlord2012", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Batman", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/WizardsOfTheLostKingdom2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/StarWars", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/JacobsLadder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Animorphs", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/CircleOfMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/JourneyToTheWest", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheWheelOfTime", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/StarWarsLegends", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheRedTent", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/NKJemisin", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheBible", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DragonBallXenoverse", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Overwatch", "/pm